name: glucosamine-1-phosphate N-acetyltransferase
classes: Transferring groups other than aminoacyl groups
comment: The enzyme from several bacteria (e.g., Escherichia coli, Bacillus subtilis and Haemophilus influenzae) has been shown to be bifunctional and also to possess the activity of EC 2.7.7.23, UDP-N-acetylglucosamine diphosphorylase.

pathways.ec00520: Amino sugar and nucleotide sugar metabolism

references.title: Copurification of glucosamine-1-phosphate acetyltransferase and N-acetylglucosamine-1-phosphate uridyltransferase activities of Escherichia coli: characterization of the glmU gene product as a bifunctional enzyme catalyzing two subsequent steps in the pathway for UDP-N-acetylglucosamine synthesis.
Acetyltransfer precedes uridylyltransfer in the formation of UDP-N-acetylglucosamine in separable active sites of the bifunctional GlmU protein of Escherichia coli.
Structure of the Escherichia coli GlmU pyrophosphorylase and acetyltransferase active sites.
